Q23: I loved laughing and joking around with close friends as early as I can remember, but never gave thought to pursuing anything to do with it. I became lost after (for a variety of reasons both in & out of my control) hockey slipped away from me at age 16 and got into substance abuse. At 17, I had ‘an incident’ with Acid and was diagnosed as LSD psychotic. It was a horrible time. I saw countless psychiatrists, and was ill to the point of being offered an indefinite home as an in-patient at a Psychiatric unit for such disorders - many of the patients remained there for life. I was heavily medicated on anti-psychotics, and decided against that, instead opting to be an out-patient. Extensive therapy helped immensely, but two things truly changed my world for the better. 1) watching Seinfeld and laughing my ass off, and 2) writing what typically ended up being humorous twists on life as a whole. I pursued the writing in high school as a journalism student, and through a variety of fortunate events and insights into why I enjoyed writing, I began to suspect that Stand Up Comedy, something Id never watched or in any way shape or form aspired to do, may be ultimately what I’d enjoy doing, so I tried it, and I was right. Hook, line, and sinker, I was caught.

Q23: I suffer from depression and was diagnosed when I was 23. I always wanted to be an actress who was good at comedy. I would watch I Love Lucy and The Dick Van Dyke Show with my dad every time I was home sick from school. I loved Sally in The Dick Van Dyke Show. A single woman who hung out with funny guys all day and had her own life. I didn't realize that's who she was at the time, I just thought she was smart and funny. Lucy was just herself no matter what. I admired that these two women had strong points of view and did what they wanted. I know that now but as a kid I just thought they were funny. I still lack a strong point of view in my comedy because I use it as a need to please, I'll say anything that'll get a laugh. My parents were pretty volatile growing up. I could be screamed at/berated and hit for doing something that didn't bother them the day before. So to this day I have confidence issues and I use performing to combat negative self talk. What's hard for me in the improv/acting scene is I have to be social more than I like; when I get depressed I turn inward and won't leave my house. With performing I can't be isolated, I need to interact with my ensemble and I always feel better being around people than being isolated. I do struggle with finding the energy on stage when I feel a depression coming on and I do have brain fog, which impacts my listening and reaction time. That can be frustrating. What I like about performing and comedy is that you can always get better. I have never met a performer who is like, Done! I'm the perfect performer now. I like that the goal is always improving on the craft. At work, as a property manager, I know I'm always learning but honestly it's not the same. The ownership I have over my talent is far more important than the ownership I have over a leaking faucet.

Q154: I am very appreciative of comedians and actors on the scene being open and addressing their own mental health challenges to try and etch away at the stigma around it.  My mom is bipolar and both of my sisters have extreme anxiety/depression, and my mom made us swear to keep it a secret.  We were never allowed to talk about it, which I think closed me off from forming many close relationships growing up.  One of my sisters is a stand-up comedian and the other is a film maker, and I'm really proud at how they are open and engaging discussions on mental health.  Our mom isn't there yet, but I felt brave enough to use the words "mental illness" with her during a phone conversation a few weeks ago.  She didn't like it, but she also didn't "go off."  I'd say that's progress, and I would love if the comedy and arts communities can continue moving the discussion in an enlightened direction.

Q23: It's a bit addictive in that I did 20-minute sets for two years and it wasn't enough. So I started a theater company. Our work involves memoir plays in which we theatrically show in which we recreate scenes and interpret what's going on in our minds that often falls into a dark comedy style. My theater company had its inaugural show this past Sept. 16 that featured seven soloists including yours truly who did personal stories that were often confessionals. In my show on the 16th I confessed my 19 years of clinical depression that my friends in the audience, some 20 people, never knew about. It was terrifically received and very liberating. I'm now planning a benefit in support of National Mental Health month for May. If you would like to interview me, do contact me at pmproduction@earthlink.net. My show on the 16th was filmed and I'm currently editing. Two of my other pieces are on Youtube at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xwwNMBFf0jM and at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VHI6mDQYcWc.

Hi, there's a lot of reasons why I'm into comedy. But one of the main reasons is because I see it as something immensely purposeful. Something that can shift culture and the world around me in a more positive direction. I wouldn't say I'm all about "getting a laugh" to me it's more about, "giving a laugh." It's using the funny talent you've been given and having the guts and discipline to go out and give it to the world. It's about fixing your frame of mind to help someone else. Saying something that makes some enjoy the moment! Laughter is incredible and contagious energy. I wouldn't say it always comes from a need to fuel your own egotism. Aside from being altruistic, it can also be a rather nice way of telling someone or someone's ideas to fuck off, a defense.

I don't really seem to fit with your survey. Sometimes I feel depressed, but I wouldn't say I have depression. I get to addicted to things... Helplessly addicted to things like Facebook, Instagram, LinkedIn or touching my iPhone. Things that are designed to toy and puppeteer my brain. We all get addicted to things. Smarter people just get addicted to things that are productive and they call them good habits. I care enough about my health not to do drugs, because I know I'd get addicted to them too. And drugs cost a lot of money!

I don't like the system created for comedians, the bars and clubs. I'v done stand-up a handful of times but I wouldn't want to put myself through that gauntlet because it seems like low-life culture.

My goal is to be writer, Second City offers and inspiring path because it's an institution based on being funny. It's a way to be connected to a community who values funny. Because comedy is a valuable business, making people laugh is worth something! It makes a life of comedy feel uplifting, hopeful... open-mics at a dingy bar or shitty small-town local comedy circuit, not the same feeling.

I've had depression, I've attempted suicide, blah blah blah - but these things I would consider reactionary to a larger problem, which is a general (what I'd consider) "brokenness" with society that comedians inherently respond to, whereas conventional people might attempt to conform or see themselves as having the problem. (This text box is one inch, so I hope this makes sense.)
Q23: My two cents: I think contemporary American culture tends to fetishize "brokenness." Yes, I've experienced depression; yes, I've been medicated; yes, I've attempted suicide - none of these ultimately are my problem so much the predictable outcome to growing up in a world that's bat-shit bonkers. If you think of society like Fukushima, comedians are the volunteers running into the reactor. Re: mental health, many of us exhibit radiation burns, but... c'mon, world... you built that nuclear plant, put it on the Ring of Fire, and all the laypeople are just standing around, surprised that shit's falling apart. So... do comedians tend to skew "eccentric/busted/certifiable" on the mental health scale? Sure. But in the bigger scheme of things, are we probably the only normal people in this world? Uh, yeah.

Yes, we want someone beautiful or someone we find attractive and someone to spend quality time with that shares our same interest.  But in actuality, we're looking for someone who can and will put up with a shit forever!  Then with all this being said, some of us feel the need to tell anyone and everyone we know and don't know our POV of the world.  Also, take for example when you travel, most of us will tell a stranger at a bar, airport, or our taxi/Uber/Lyft driver our entire life story.  People enjoy telling their deepest darkest secrets and POVs to strangers, it's a natural high and stress reliever.  And people love hearing them, too, especially if they're funny.

Q23: Greetings! I am also a PhD in Clinical Psychology and producer of the first and only conference on Mental Health and Improvisation, so this topic is clearly at the core of my passion.  My best guess is that this survey is at the undergrad/graduate level, academic-wise, as there are many holes to the questions and phrasings you have involved here.  There ARE scholastic articles on the mental health of individuals who work in comedy, so the opening statement of the survey is not accurate.  At least as it was written. Google search "mental health and comedians" and you'll get an array of articles and professionals studying the subject matter.   Also, as stated before, Stand-Up comedy is not the only type of "comedian" who works in the industry.  There are comedic writers, comedic performers, improvisers, etc.,.  I wish you luck as you dive further into this topic.  You have a very basic start here and much more is needed as we explore this incredibly valuable subject matter.

Q154: It seems like everyone in comedy is dealing with some sort of depression or anxiety. Even if someone isn’t diagnosed, it seems like there’s usually something. Parks and Rec has a great line that’s something like “You’re too pretty to have needed to be funny” and I relate so much to that. Comedy is more than a coping mechanism - it’s a way of subverting social norms and hierarchies. Throughout history, the only person more powerful than a king was their jester. Jesters could make fun of anything serious and get praised instead of killed. Jokes give the joke teller power of over their situation. I was funny before I got ptsd, but I can trace the realization I was funny back to my very awkward puberty. Being funny got me through middle school.
